    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. the capacity issue with vectors is a good point, i'll check our telemetry logs for that. it feels like there's something just \"lurking\" in the code and only showing up when the system is under sustained load. how can i distinguish between a genuine leak and just high fragmentation causing the available RAM to appear lower?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Distinguishing a genuine leak from fragmentation is like trying to tell if a pile of discarded trash is actually a persistent, growing pile of garbage or just a jumble of old refuse. The key difference is persistence over time and predictable growth. A genuine leak will show a monotonic increase in memory usage—it keeps climbing, even if the system is idle for a while. Fragmentation, on the other hand, usually results in the system having *enough* total free memory, but none of it is in one contiguous block large enough for the next allocation.\n\nTo test this, you need to introduce a controlled \"reset\" or \"idle\" period. If you let the system run for a few hours, and then force a complete, controlled shutdown and restart (a hard reboot, if possible), and the memory usage returns to the baseline, it was likely fragmentation or transient usage. If the memory usage *never* drops back to the baseline after a full reset, you have a leak. If it *does* drop, but the next run starts higher than the previous one, you have a leak.",
      "source": "target",
